nihamba)-once performed while traversing vast distances to the accompaniment of the European mouth-harp (isitweletwele)-she uncovers the manifold impacts of internationally-driven transboundary environmental conservation on land, livelihoods, and local senses of place. This book links ethnomusicological research to larger themes of international development, environmental conservation, gender, and local economic access to resources. By demonstrating that development processes are essentially cultural processes and revealing how music fits within this frame, Song Walking testifies to the affective, spatial, and economic dimensions of place, while contributing to a more inclusive and culturally apposite alignment between land and environmental policies and local needs and practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aEcomusicologyzSouth AfricazMaputaland. 0aEcomusicology-South Africa-Maputaland. 0aJew's harpxSocial aspectszSouth AfricazMaputaland. 0aJew's harp-Social aspects-South Africa-Maputaland. 0aMaputaland (South Africa)-Social life and customs. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszSouth AfricazMaputaland. 0aMusic-Social aspects-South Africa-Maputaland. 0aWomenzSouth AfricazMaputalandxSocial life and customs. 0aWomen-South Africa-Maputaland-Social life and customs. 4aborder landscape. 4aenvironmental justice. 4amemory. 4asoutheast Africa. 4awalking songs. 4awomen. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226538150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226538150.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles